---
import GeneratorPage from '../components/generator/GeneratorPage.astro';
import { getPreset } from '../lib/styles';

const preset = getPreset('fantasy-characters');
const title = 'AI D&D Character Portrait Generator — Free & Unlimited';
const description =
  'Generate fantasy character portraits for D&D, Pathfinder and any TTRPG. Free, unlimited, no signup — the AI runs in your browser on your own GPU.';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'Can I use a portrait for my character sheet / campaign / stream?', a: 'Yes — commercial use of outputs is permitted by the model licence. Character sheets, campaign notes, VTT tokens, Twitch overlays: all fine.' },
  { q: 'How do I get the same character twice?', a: 'Lock the seed and keep the prompt identical — you will get the same image. Small prompt edits with a locked seed produce variations of roughly the same character. True multi-pose consistency needs bigger tools; for portraits, seed-locking covers most needs.' },
  { q: 'Can it draw my whole party in one image?', a: 'Multi-character scenes are the weak spot of a single-step model — faces blur and limbs merge. Generate each member separately; the shared style keeps the set looking coherent.' },
  { q: 'The face looks odd. What do I do?', a: 'Reroll — seeds vary wildly on faces. Adding "detailed face" is already in this page\'s styling; specifying age, expression and one distinctive feature ("scar over left eye") helps the model commit.' },
  { q: 'Does it know D&D races and classes?', a: 'The base model was trained on enormous amounts of fantasy art, so tieflings, dragonborn, drow, paladins and warlocks all render recognisably. Rarer homebrew concepts work best described physically ("a fox-headed humanoid monk in orange robes").' },
];
---

<GeneratorPage
  preset={preset}
  title={title}
  h1="Fantasy Character Portraits"
  description={description}
  intro="Your character, visualised. Describe race, class and one memorable detail — dramatic fantasy-art styling is applied automatically."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Session zero, sorted</h2>
  <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-6">
    Every player knows the gap between the character in their head and the stock art on their sheet.
    Commissioned art is wonderful and costs real money per character; free portrait sites are a carousel
    of the same elves. Here you type "a grizzled human paladin in dented plate armour", wait three
    seconds, and reroll until the face matches the voice you've been doing at the table. NPCs too — a GM
    can portrait an entire village in one evening, for nothing.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-10">Describing a character the model understands</h2>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">Race + class + age:</strong> "an elderly dwarven cleric" anchors the whole face.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">One signature item:</strong> the glowing tome, the braided beard, the cracked mask — a single memorable detail beats five adjectives.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">Expression = personality:</strong> "grinning", "weary", "serene" — the model is good at faces carrying mood.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-[color:var(--color-text)]">Colour-code your party:</strong> give each member a palette ("green cloak", "crimson robes") so the set reads as one campaign.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-10">Tokens for your VTT</h2>
  <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-mute)] leading-relaxed mb-6">
    The square 512×512 output drops straight into Foundry, Roll20 or Owlbear Rodeo as a portrait. For
    round tokens, any token-maker tool crops these cleanly — the "upper body, centered" styling this page
    applies was chosen with exactly that crop in mind.
  </p>
</GeneratorPage>
